00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:50.270
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:38:50.270 --> 00:38:53.540
First of all, thank you
for coming to Google.

00:38:53.540 --> 00:38:56.210
I have a question
about forgiveness

00:38:56.210 --> 00:38:59.300
and how it might
be different when

00:38:59.300 --> 00:39:01.700
the person you are forgiving,
or the people that you

00:39:01.700 --> 00:39:06.990
are forgiving, feel bad
versus don't feel bad.

00:39:06.990 --> 00:39:10.880
So in the case of the
doctor who you spoke with

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:14.840
and who expressed to you that
he felt terrible every day,

00:39:14.840 --> 00:39:19.460
it seems like that would aid in
being able to feel forgiveness,

00:39:19.460 --> 00:39:24.590
whereas presumably
there are Nazis who

00:39:24.590 --> 00:39:26.330
still are alive who might not--

00:39:26.330 --> 00:39:29.780
who don't feel that
way, who don't feel bad.

00:39:29.780 --> 00:39:32.780
How do you feel forgiveness
for those people?

00:39:34.895 --> 00:39:37.170
EVA KOR: Because of
forgiveness, if we understand it

00:39:37.170 --> 00:39:38.920
correctly today--

00:39:38.920 --> 00:39:44.070
I agree with you that when it
happened it was helpful to me

00:39:44.070 --> 00:39:50.500
that he was feeling sorry and
remorse in what he has done.

00:39:50.500 --> 00:39:53.130
If he would have yelled
at me and treated me

00:39:53.130 --> 00:39:55.320
like a good old
Nazi in the camp,

00:39:55.320 --> 00:39:56.880
I probably would
not have not been

00:39:56.880 --> 00:40:01.560
able to reach a
forgiveness or even want

00:40:01.560 --> 00:40:03.370
to deal with him at all.

00:40:03.370 --> 00:40:07.290
So these steps that happened,
happened accidentally.

00:40:07.290 --> 00:40:13.080
But once I realized what the
power that the forgiveness has,

00:40:13.080 --> 00:40:14.820
I do not care.

00:40:14.820 --> 00:40:17.640
I am sorry if they
feel still angry,

00:40:17.640 --> 00:40:20.730
and they want to
create problems.

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:21.930
I have the right.

00:40:21.930 --> 00:40:27.685
And it's a fairly selfish thing,
but it does not hurt anybody.

00:40:27.685 --> 00:40:31.510
It helps everybody, that
I do have the human right.

00:40:31.510 --> 00:40:34.260
And actually, I am
trying to get the United

00:40:34.260 --> 00:40:37.710
Nations to change
their Universal

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:39.540
Declaration to Human Rights.

00:40:39.540 --> 00:40:44.110
That every human being on
the face of this earth--

00:40:44.110 --> 00:40:46.460
an addendum that I
would like to add--

00:40:46.460 --> 00:40:52.080
has the human right to be happy
and to be free of the pain

00:40:52.080 --> 00:40:55.110
that anybody imposed
us in the past.

00:40:55.110 --> 00:40:59.100
And we can do it if we
so choose by forgiving.

00:40:59.100 --> 00:41:01.710
So the ideal of
forgiveness, I would

00:41:01.710 --> 00:41:05.760
like it to be a human right
included into the declaration.

00:41:05.760 --> 00:41:11.130
But the fact that they
are still mean and nasty,

00:41:11.130 --> 00:41:15.420
it's more that I have the
need to forgive them, and thus

00:41:15.420 --> 00:41:18.990
remove them from my agenda.

00:41:18.990 --> 00:41:19.908
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:41:19.908 --> 00:41:22.000
EVA KOR: You're welcome.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:22.670
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:22.670 --> 00:41:23.190
Thank you.

00:41:23.190 --> 00:41:25.880
So my question is, do you
consider the forgiveness

00:41:25.880 --> 00:41:28.070
to the start of the
healing process,

00:41:28.070 --> 00:41:31.220
or do you consider possibility
of the healing started before,

00:41:31.220 --> 00:41:32.930
even before forgiveness,
and forgiveness

00:41:32.930 --> 00:41:35.950
being a stage of that.

00:41:35.950 --> 00:41:38.626
EVA KOR: I'm not
sure that I follow.

00:41:38.626 --> 00:41:40.500
TED GREEN: Do you need
to forgive-- let's see

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:41.583
if I'm hearing this right.

00:41:41.583 --> 00:41:43.280
Do you need to be
able to forgive

00:41:43.280 --> 00:41:44.750
before you can start healing?

00:41:44.750 --> 00:41:47.754
Or can you heal sometimes
before you forgive?

00:41:47.754 --> 00:41:48.920
AUDIENCE: Yes, that's right.

00:41:48.920 --> 00:41:50.270
EVA KOR: You have to forgive.

00:41:50.270 --> 00:41:53.630
Because by forgiving,
you are removing

00:41:53.630 --> 00:41:56.370
all the pain and the burden.

00:41:56.370 --> 00:41:58.070
Although, one more thing.

00:41:58.070 --> 00:42:02.210
Forgiveness gives you
power over your life.

00:42:02.210 --> 00:42:05.990
And most victims when
they are victimized

00:42:05.990 --> 00:42:08.240
and after, they
feel they have they

00:42:08.240 --> 00:42:12.120
have no power to
change their life.

00:42:12.120 --> 00:42:13.290
Many people.

00:42:13.290 --> 00:42:14.840
So what can I do about it?

00:42:14.840 --> 00:42:16.470
That's it.

00:42:16.470 --> 00:42:22.520
But by having that power that
we all do, we exist in every--

00:42:22.520 --> 00:42:26.870
even in wars where there is a
lot more problems than here,

00:42:26.870 --> 00:42:28.610
we do have the power to forgive.

00:42:28.610 --> 00:42:30.450
We don't have to make it public.

00:42:30.450 --> 00:42:32.590
But we know that we forgive.

00:42:32.590 --> 00:42:36.830
Therefore, the burden of pain
is removed from our shoulder.

00:42:36.830 --> 00:42:38.525
And this is when
the healing starts.

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:47.960
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank you
for coming to speak to us.

00:42:47.960 --> 00:42:51.170
As you know, we are
technology builders.

00:42:51.170 --> 00:42:56.180
We build telephones and
communications systems,

00:42:56.180 --> 00:42:59.630
information tools.

00:42:59.630 --> 00:43:02.420
You've been living a
life of great purpose

00:43:02.420 --> 00:43:07.340
through a time of great
technological transformation

00:43:07.340 --> 00:43:09.200
through the 20th century.

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:12.440
I wonder if you can
think of any time

00:43:12.440 --> 00:43:16.460
maybe recently, maybe
a long time ago,

00:43:16.460 --> 00:43:20.270
of a technology that
helped you achieve

00:43:20.270 --> 00:43:29.050
your purposes in your work for
remembrance and for justice

00:43:29.050 --> 00:43:30.942
and for forgiveness.

00:43:30.942 --> 00:43:33.790
EVA KOR: Well, it's an
interesting question.

00:43:33.790 --> 00:43:36.520
I do not agree with
the word justice.

00:43:36.520 --> 00:43:38.110
Only just punishment.

00:43:38.110 --> 00:43:41.770
But I don't think there is
really justice in the world.

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:47.470
But purpose, I mean,
technology, I am not sure

00:43:47.470 --> 00:43:50.710
if I am going to answer it.

00:43:50.710 --> 00:43:55.630
How can I help using
technology in my philosophy

00:43:55.630 --> 00:43:58.210
of forgiveness?

00:43:58.210 --> 00:44:01.940
The Shoah Foundation
created holograms.

00:44:01.940 --> 00:44:04.000
And I have a hologram of my own.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.240
There are certain
survivors who were

00:44:06.240 --> 00:44:11.380
recorded for hologram,
interactive holograms.

00:44:11.380 --> 00:44:16.450
I think the idea that we
can spread the knowledge

00:44:16.450 --> 00:44:20.720
and information
that each of us has.

00:44:20.720 --> 00:44:23.560
And we can interact,
and by interacting, we

00:44:23.560 --> 00:44:28.810
can help other people maybe
realize that they can do it too

00:44:28.810 --> 00:44:29.980
in their own way.

00:44:29.980 --> 00:44:34.630
I don't think that everybody
will do healing and forgiveness

00:44:34.630 --> 00:44:35.620
in my way--

00:44:35.620 --> 00:44:36.460
own way.

00:44:36.460 --> 00:44:40.210
Technology-- I mean, he
created a wonderful film

00:44:40.210 --> 00:44:43.270
with a lot of
technological parts.

00:44:43.270 --> 00:44:47.020
And that we are also going to
make available for schools.

00:44:49.706 --> 00:44:51.540
I do not know--

00:44:51.540 --> 00:44:54.040
I will tell you one thing
that I'm fascinated.

00:44:54.040 --> 00:44:56.840
I am fascinated by
all these questions.

00:44:56.840 --> 00:45:00.580
Do you know that the
most interesting part

00:45:00.580 --> 00:45:04.956
in the human body is the brain?

00:45:04.956 --> 00:45:09.220
Everything that
we come up with--

00:45:09.220 --> 00:45:13.310
I mean, I'm amazed how long
ago, over 100 years ago,

00:45:13.310 --> 00:45:15.280
people came up with ideas.

00:45:15.280 --> 00:45:17.930
Columbus discovered America.

00:45:17.930 --> 00:45:21.460
The curiosities that we have.

00:45:21.460 --> 00:45:23.780
We can do anything.

00:45:23.780 --> 00:45:27.670
Therefore, I am convinced
that we can heal

00:45:27.670 --> 00:45:29.500
all the problems in the world.

00:45:29.500 --> 00:45:32.920
If I just gave you
an assignment here,

00:45:32.920 --> 00:45:37.560
every single one of you,
if you ever are bored,

00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:40.540
just think for 10
minutes, what can I

00:45:40.540 --> 00:45:43.940
do to make the world better?

00:45:43.940 --> 00:45:46.520
I don't care how little it is.

00:45:46.520 --> 00:45:49.610
But every single one
of you can do something

00:45:49.610 --> 00:45:51.780
to make the world better.

00:45:51.780 --> 00:45:56.940
Now, if we can use
technology to enhance that,

00:45:56.940 --> 00:46:00.310
that is where the
power of technology is.

00:46:00.310 --> 00:46:01.560
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:46:01.560 --> 00:46:03.480
TED GREEN: Can I jump
in on this one as well?

00:46:03.480 --> 00:46:04.896
I don't think
you're going to find

00:46:04.896 --> 00:46:08.471
many more technology savvy
84-year-olds than this women

00:46:08.471 --> 00:46:08.970
right here.

00:46:08.970 --> 00:46:10.590
I mean, she's got an app.

00:46:10.590 --> 00:46:12.570
She tweets all the time.

00:46:12.570 --> 00:46:16.550
And actually, she delivers
her lectures via Skype.

00:46:16.550 --> 00:46:19.120
She gets requests from
all over the world.

00:46:19.120 --> 00:46:21.810
So she really has
been, you know,

00:46:21.810 --> 00:46:24.120
back in the days
in the 1980s, when

00:46:24.120 --> 00:46:26.940
all of your typed-written
letters to every publication

00:46:26.940 --> 00:46:30.510
around the country just asking
them to help with your story.

00:46:30.510 --> 00:46:32.070
And here you are
and she is really

00:46:32.070 --> 00:46:33.990
reaching all around the world.

00:46:33.990 --> 00:46:36.370
EVA KOR: And I found my
typewriter, if I'm moving,

00:46:36.370 --> 00:46:38.580
the old typewriter I
found in the garage.

00:46:38.580 --> 00:46:39.508
TED GREEN: All right.

00:46:42.772 --> 00:46:44.230
AUDIENCE: Hi, first
of all, my name

00:46:44.230 --> 00:46:46.313
is Rina like your daughter's
name. that's really--

00:46:46.313 --> 00:46:47.560
EVA KOR: Oh, wonderful.

00:46:47.560 --> 00:46:49.900
AUDIENCE: Thank you
so much for coming.

00:46:49.900 --> 00:46:54.120
I wanted to ask so in terms of
the Holocaust, what happened

00:46:54.120 --> 00:46:56.200
overall, like a
genocide and whatnot,

00:46:56.200 --> 00:46:58.750
do you think that
we, as a globe,

00:46:58.750 --> 00:47:03.460
have learned from
that terrible event,

00:47:03.460 --> 00:47:08.830
or do you think that
there's still more to learn?

00:47:08.830 --> 00:47:13.450
EVA KOR: I think that
technology and communication

00:47:13.450 --> 00:47:17.900
and the internet and
I will tell you why.

00:47:17.900 --> 00:47:20.560
For instance, as
we sit here, there

00:47:20.560 --> 00:47:25.150
are many people in the world who
are suffering, lack of freedom,

00:47:25.150 --> 00:47:28.290
lack of food, lack
of many things.

00:47:28.290 --> 00:47:33.640
But it was New Year's
Eve, and I said, well,

00:47:33.640 --> 00:47:35.410
I am not going to
go anywhere, but I

00:47:35.410 --> 00:47:37.510
want to do something unique.

00:47:37.510 --> 00:47:40.140
So I was going to help--

00:47:40.140 --> 00:47:42.850
the Iranian issue
was on the news.

00:47:42.850 --> 00:47:45.040
They talked about the protests.

00:47:45.040 --> 00:47:51.250
Those people are living in
theocracy without any freedom.

00:47:51.250 --> 00:47:55.030
It's hard for us to understand
because in the United States,

00:47:55.030 --> 00:47:59.370
we really have the most freedom
that most people would have.

00:47:59.370 --> 00:48:02.080
Economically, it's
very important,

00:48:02.080 --> 00:48:05.470
because if you don't have food,
you cannot be very free, right?

00:48:05.470 --> 00:48:07.210
If you don't have money to buy.

00:48:07.210 --> 00:48:12.970
So we can, all of
us, do something

00:48:12.970 --> 00:48:17.170
and in helping other
people in preventing--

00:48:17.170 --> 00:48:22.390
I mean, how on earth that
Iran was able to protest?

00:48:22.390 --> 00:48:23.020
The internet.

00:48:23.020 --> 00:48:26.340
So I tweeted.

00:48:26.340 --> 00:48:27.490
I tweeted.

00:48:27.490 --> 00:48:28.560
I did the following.

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:34.740
I said 73, years ago, we
were dying in the Nazi camps,

00:48:34.740 --> 00:48:36.350
and the world was silent.

00:48:39.690 --> 00:48:43.440
And I got about 26 responses.

00:48:43.440 --> 00:48:45.540
I didn't like it.

00:48:45.540 --> 00:48:49.940
So I said, 73 years ago,
I was dying in Auschwitz,

00:48:49.940 --> 00:48:51.520
and the world was silent.

00:48:51.520 --> 00:48:54.060
And I no longer can be silent.

00:48:54.060 --> 00:48:59.250
I want you to join with me
and tweet for freedom of Iran.

00:48:59.250 --> 00:49:04.350
I got 17,000 responses.

00:49:04.350 --> 00:49:05.640
So it pays to be dramatic.

00:49:08.160 --> 00:49:16.170
But also the fact that they
entered me in direct mail,

00:49:16.170 --> 00:49:18.930
they said, nobody
has their stories.

00:49:18.930 --> 00:49:21.210
They didn't know
if their stories

00:49:21.210 --> 00:49:23.380
were carried by the media.

00:49:23.380 --> 00:49:30.800
And me tweeting helped them
find out that we knew about it.

00:49:30.800 --> 00:49:32.460
Of course, they were arrested.

00:49:32.460 --> 00:49:34.680
I don't know what their
destiny is right now.

00:49:34.680 --> 00:49:36.020
But I don't think--

00:49:36.020 --> 00:49:38.310
here and there I
get some direct mail

00:49:38.310 --> 00:49:42.170
that we are still
planning something.

00:49:42.170 --> 00:49:46.120
So this is a way I have
a little bit of doubt

00:49:46.120 --> 00:49:49.940
that easily it
can be pulled off.

00:49:49.940 --> 00:49:54.920
Because direct mail,
direct message,

00:49:54.920 --> 00:49:57.740
cannot completely be eradicated.

00:49:57.740 --> 00:50:02.480
The technology is
helping break through.

00:50:02.480 --> 00:50:04.980
That people have not
learned their lesson,

00:50:04.980 --> 00:50:06.110
that is another tragedy.

00:50:12.860 --> 00:50:14.720
AUDIENCE: Thank you, Eva.

00:50:14.720 --> 00:50:19.970
You seem to have an immense
liveliness and vitality.

00:50:19.970 --> 00:50:24.200
And I just wonder where
do you get it from?

00:50:24.200 --> 00:50:25.550
What drives you?

00:50:25.550 --> 00:50:27.980
EVA KOR: Well, then
Mengele stood by my bed

00:50:27.980 --> 00:50:31.160
and said that I had
only two weeks to live,

00:50:31.160 --> 00:50:34.160
I was going to prove him wrong.

00:50:34.160 --> 00:50:37.730
And I had been trying to prove
the world wrong ever since.

00:50:37.730 --> 00:50:40.490
I don't know.

00:50:40.490 --> 00:50:44.930
I feel I was in the
hospital a year ago in May,

00:50:44.930 --> 00:50:47.870
and I was supposed to
give the big speech,

00:50:47.870 --> 00:50:53.390
that it was a terrific
speech, about medicine

00:50:53.390 --> 00:50:55.280
and law and the Holocaust.

00:50:55.280 --> 00:50:57.740
OK, that's combined everything.

00:50:57.740 --> 00:51:00.750
And I worked very hard on it.

00:51:00.750 --> 00:51:03.380
And I was rushed into
the emergency room

00:51:03.380 --> 00:51:05.600
for not being able--

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:07.490
my heart was in big trouble.

00:51:07.490 --> 00:51:11.810
It wasn't beating
more than 0 to 40.

00:51:11.810 --> 00:51:15.590
And he was there at
the emergency room.

00:51:15.590 --> 00:51:20.600
I said, Ted, this is the
best speech I ever wrote.

00:51:20.600 --> 00:51:22.360
He said, I talked
to the doctors.

00:51:22.360 --> 00:51:27.350
Can I get two hours
off to give my speech?

00:51:27.350 --> 00:51:31.680
And they said, no, what if you
die while you give the speech

00:51:31.680 --> 00:51:33.590
and we don't have the equipment.

00:51:33.590 --> 00:51:37.430
I said, oh, god, that too.

00:51:37.430 --> 00:51:40.160
So Ted recorded it.

00:51:40.160 --> 00:51:43.580
And then I rolled into
the operating room

00:51:43.580 --> 00:51:48.050
to get my pacemaker,
and my recording

00:51:48.050 --> 00:51:50.700
got a standing ovation.

00:51:50.700 --> 00:51:53.000
But I didn't meet Elena Kagan.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.047
So she was in the audience.

00:51:55.047 --> 00:51:55.880
I couldn't meet her.

00:51:55.880 --> 00:51:59.399
I said maybe she would come to
the hospital, but she didn't.

00:51:59.399 --> 00:52:01.190
TED GREEN: It was
actually really something

00:52:01.190 --> 00:52:03.030
because they were the
co-keynote speakers.

00:52:03.030 --> 00:52:05.660
And I will have to say, no
offense to the Supreme Court

00:52:05.660 --> 00:52:08.480
Justice, but Eva's
taped speech got

00:52:08.480 --> 00:52:12.650
a much bigger round of applause
than Elena Kagan's did.

00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:15.401
EVA KOR: So where do I--

00:52:15.401 --> 00:52:16.710
I don't really know.

00:52:16.710 --> 00:52:18.290
I think some of it is genetic.

00:52:18.290 --> 00:52:21.140
Most of it probably
comes from my mother

00:52:21.140 --> 00:52:24.242
who I don't think
she ever thought

00:52:24.242 --> 00:52:26.090
she would be living
in a big farm

00:52:26.090 --> 00:52:29.360
in a godforsaken little village.

00:52:29.360 --> 00:52:33.290
And she found joy and
happiness in what she could.

00:52:33.290 --> 00:52:35.210
And she loved her children.

00:52:35.210 --> 00:52:38.310
And she loved being
the woman that she was.

00:52:38.310 --> 00:52:43.140
As she was arguing with my
father about her [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:43.140 --> 00:52:45.540
little daughters,
because my father--

00:52:45.540 --> 00:52:48.530
we were religious,
very, Orthodox Jews.

00:52:48.530 --> 00:52:50.600
And my father said,
oh, the girl just

00:52:50.600 --> 00:52:53.390
need to get married and
have babies and that is.

00:52:53.390 --> 00:52:57.530
My mother said, no, my girls
are going to get an education.

00:52:57.530 --> 00:53:00.830
And she never gave up on that.

00:53:00.830 --> 00:53:04.550
So as I was going to
college for 11 years,

00:53:04.550 --> 00:53:08.330
every time I was struggling,
the voice of my mother

00:53:08.330 --> 00:53:11.230
was ringing in my
ears, "My children

00:53:11.230 --> 00:53:13.310
are going to get an education."

00:53:13.310 --> 00:53:16.490
And her vitality,
and her joy, she

00:53:16.490 --> 00:53:21.740
would iron my father's
shirt with an iron

00:53:21.740 --> 00:53:24.410
that had the charcoal in it.

00:53:24.410 --> 00:53:27.980
And she would put on the
radio to listen to the radio.

00:53:27.980 --> 00:53:30.740
She was happy doing
what she was doing.

00:53:30.740 --> 00:53:34.910
So find happiness
in any situation.

00:53:34.910 --> 00:53:38.500
There is always-- you
can make your life happy

00:53:38.500 --> 00:53:43.670
even when things look
desperate or not very good.

00:53:43.670 --> 00:53:45.980
Find joy in something.

00:53:45.980 --> 00:53:50.030
And I find joy in the fact
that I get up every morning,

00:53:50.030 --> 00:53:51.620
and I say, I'm still alive.

00:53:51.620 --> 00:53:53.090
Ah, that's very good.

00:53:55.800 --> 00:53:57.890
And then I see what
can I do good--

00:53:57.890 --> 00:53:59.960
what good can I do today?

00:53:59.960 --> 00:54:04.860
And that, right away,
puts me in a good mood.

00:54:04.860 --> 00:54:08.049
SPEAKER 1: We have time for
one more quick question.

00:54:08.049 --> 00:54:10.090
AUDIENCE: I was really
struck by a comment by Ted

00:54:10.090 --> 00:54:12.160
earlier where you
mentioned that there

00:54:12.160 --> 00:54:13.660
have been so many
Holocaust stories,

00:54:13.660 --> 00:54:16.240
so why is this one different.

00:54:16.240 --> 00:54:18.640
The reason that that
struck me is recent surveys

00:54:18.640 --> 00:54:20.762
have shown that as many
as 2/3 of millennials

00:54:20.762 --> 00:54:21.970
don't know what Auschwitz is.

00:54:21.970 --> 00:54:24.710
40% of Americans
don't know what it is.

00:54:24.710 --> 00:54:26.850
So with all those stories
that have been told,

00:54:26.850 --> 00:54:27.850
what are we doing wrong?

00:54:27.850 --> 00:54:30.920
And why aren't those stories
resonating and spreading?

00:54:30.920 --> 00:54:32.440
EVA KOR: That is--

00:54:32.440 --> 00:54:34.610
I don't know if I
can answer that.

00:54:34.610 --> 00:54:38.620
I think that the
curriculum in schools

00:54:38.620 --> 00:54:44.650
have to include the idea
that history is important.

00:54:44.650 --> 00:54:48.220
We are the product of the past.

00:54:48.220 --> 00:54:53.030
And we have to rely on what
happened before to go forward.

00:54:53.030 --> 00:54:55.540
This country was
founded, and we have

00:54:55.540 --> 00:54:57.850
to learn the history
of this country.

00:54:57.850 --> 00:55:02.830
So many Americans have
died in World War II.

00:55:02.830 --> 00:55:05.820
So many millions of people
died in World War II.

00:55:05.820 --> 00:55:08.830
That has to be a pretty
big event in the world

00:55:08.830 --> 00:55:12.700
to have a bigger chapter
in the high school

00:55:12.700 --> 00:55:14.650
and junior high school books.

00:55:14.650 --> 00:55:17.260
And why doesn't it?

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:19.550
Because it is an
important chapter.

00:55:19.550 --> 00:55:22.520
And what do we learn from it?

00:55:22.520 --> 00:55:25.510
I am hoping that if I
am successful enough

00:55:25.510 --> 00:55:30.730
with Ted and with what we are
doing, that I can stimulate

00:55:30.730 --> 00:55:33.460
more interest for more schools.

00:55:33.460 --> 00:55:36.350
Because the schools are
controlled by school board,

00:55:36.350 --> 00:55:39.050
and they decide
their curriculum.

00:55:39.050 --> 00:55:40.120
So we are learning.

00:55:40.120 --> 00:55:44.290
With my publisher, I have
been giving lot of lectures

00:55:44.290 --> 00:55:49.390
to school board and
[? schools ?] to adopt my book.

00:55:49.390 --> 00:55:52.840
And once they adopt my book,
they learn a little bit more

00:55:52.840 --> 00:55:54.220
to teach it.

00:55:54.220 --> 00:55:55.900
And it's a along--

00:55:55.900 --> 00:55:56.980
it's a big effort.

00:55:56.980 --> 00:55:59.640
It's not simple.

00:55:59.640 --> 00:56:04.030
But I think your point is
very well made, that we

00:56:04.030 --> 00:56:06.340
need to make a bigger effort.

00:56:06.340 --> 00:56:07.450
And all of us.

00:56:07.450 --> 00:56:08.650
Not only me.

00:56:08.650 --> 00:56:11.560
So I ask you to join me.

00:56:11.560 --> 00:56:13.690
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:56:13.690 --> 00:56:15.890
SPEAKER 1: So Ted, Eva,
thank you for being here.

00:56:15.890 --> 00:56:17.800
Thank you for
sharing your story.

00:56:17.800 --> 00:56:20.150
Again, if you want to
learn more about the film,

00:56:20.150 --> 00:56:21.250
it's TheStoryofEva.com.

00:56:21.250 --> 00:56:24.130
And so thanks for your time.

00:56:24.130 --> 00:56:26.580
[APPLAUSE]

